1. What is Inheritance?

Inheritance is one of the four pillars of Object-Oriented
Programming (OOP).

Inheritance allows one class to acquire the properties
(variables) and behaviors (methods) of another class.

The existing class is called Parent Class (Superclass).

The new class is called Child Class (Subclass).

---------------------------------------------------------

2. Why do we use Inheritance?

• Code Reusability

• Reduces Duplicate Code

• Easy Maintenance

• Improves Readability

• Supports Method Overriding

---------------------------------------------------------

3. extends Keyword

Inheritance is achieved using the extends keyword.

Syntax

class Child extends Parent{

}

Example

class Dog extends Animal{

}

---------------------------------------------------------

4. Parent Class

A class whose properties are inherited by another class.

Example

Animal

---------------------------------------------------------

5. Child Class

A class that inherits properties from another class.

Example

Dog

---------------------------------------------------------

6. Types of Inheritance

1. Single Inheritance

One Parent → One Child

Example

Animal

↓

Dog

---------------------------------------------------------

2. Multilevel Inheritance

Grand Parent

↓

Parent

↓

Child

Example

Animal

↓

Dog

↓

Puppy

---------------------------------------------------------

3. Hierarchical Inheritance

One Parent

↓

Multiple Child Classes

Example

Animal

↓

Dog

↓

Cat

---------------------------------------------------------

4. Multiple Inheritance

One Child inherits from two Parent Classes.

Java does NOT support Multiple Inheritance using classes.

Reason

Diamond Problem

However,

It can be achieved using Interfaces.

---------------------------------------------------------

5. Hybrid Inheritance

Combination of two or more inheritance types.

Java supports Hybrid Inheritance only through Interfaces.

---------------------------------------------------------

6. Advantages of Inheritance

• Code Reusability

• Less Code Duplication

• Supports Polymorphism

• Better Code Organization

• Easy Maintenance

---------------------------------------------------------

7. Method Overriding (Introduction)

Method Overriding means redefining the Parent Class method
inside the Child Class.

It provides Runtime Polymorphism.

---------------------------------------------------------

